    avsColYear: 'Year', avsColStart: 'Value start', avsColDepr: 'Depreciation', avsColEnd: 'Value end', avsRegPctLabel:'Depreciation rate (%)', avsLifeLabel:'Useful life (years)', avsScrapLabel:'Residual value (%)', avsRegTableHeader:'Straight-line depreciation schedule', avsCmpTableHeader:'Comparison: Tax vs. Accounting', avsModeSkatt:'Tax', avsModeRegnskap:'Accounting', avsModeCompare:'Compare', avsCmpSkatt:'Tax (declining balance)', avsCmpRegnskap:'Accounting (straight-line)', avsCmpDiff:'Difference', avsTotal:'Total', avsCmpNote:'Positive difference = accounting depreciation is higher → deferred tax liability. Negative difference = tax depreciation is higher → deferred tax asset.', avsRegnskapInfo:'Straight-line depreciation per the Accounting Act § 5-3. The asset is depreciated evenly over its expected useful life, down to any residual value.', avsIntroSkatt:'Tax depreciation (declining balance): the asset is written down by a fixed percentage of the remaining value each year. Select the depreciation group based on asset type.', avsIntroRegnskap:'Accounting depreciation per the <strong>Accounting Act § 5-3</strong>: fixed assets with limited useful life shall be depreciated according to a reasonable depreciation plan. Straight-line method distributes cost evenly over the useful life.', avsIntroCompare:'Compare tax declining-balance depreciation with accounting straight-line depreciation. The difference shows temporary differences that affect deferred tax.', avsCmpValTitle:'Asset value', avsCmpBookVal:'Book value', avsCmpTaxVal:'Tax value', avsCmpValDiff:'Difference', avsCmpValNote:'Book value = accounting residual value (straight-line depreciation). Tax value = declining balance value. Difference = book − tax. Positive difference → deferred tax liability. Negative difference → deferred tax asset. Values are based on the inputs from the comparison above.',
    avsCmpEffTitle:'Tax effect of temporary differences', avsCmpEffDiff:'Temporary difference', avsCmpEffTax:'Deferred tax (22%)', avsCmpDebtShort:'liability', avsCmpAssetShort:'asset',
    avsIntroInfo: 'A brief overview of accounting and tax depreciation.', avsLawLink: 'Tax Act §§ 14-40 to 14-48',
    avsInfoContent: '<div style="font-size:14px;font-weight:600;color:var(--ink);margin-bottom:12px;">What is depreciation?</div><div style="font-size:13px;color:var(--ink2);line-height:1.7;"><p style="margin:0 0 10px;">Depreciation means spreading the cost of a fixed asset (machinery, vehicles, buildings) over its useful life — instead of expensing everything at purchase.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;"><strong>Accounting (Accounting Act § 5-3)</strong><br>Depreciation follows a reasonable depreciation plan. Straight-line is most common, but the method should reflect expected economic consumption of the asset.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;"><strong>Tax (Tax Act §§ 14-40 to 14-48)</strong><br>Declining balance depreciation: a fixed percentage of the remaining balance each year. Higher depreciation early, lower over time. The rate depends on the depreciation group (a–j). Which group the asset is placed in has <strong>significant impact</strong> on how much tax deduction you get — a higher rate means faster deductions and lower tax in the early years. When the remaining balance falls below NOK 30,000, the entire amount can be deducted directly.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;"><strong>Why the difference?</strong><br>Because tax rules and accounting rules serve different purposes. Tax rules often provide faster deductions (incentive), while accounting rules follow the plan for actual value decline. The difference creates <em>temporary differences</em> that affect deferred tax on the balance sheet.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;"><strong>Deferred tax asset vs. liability</strong><br>When tax depreciation exceeds accounting → book value > tax value → <span style="color:var(--red,#c44);">deferred tax liability</span> (you received the tax deduction earlier than in the accounts).<br>When accounting is higher → the opposite → <span style="color:var(--green,#2a7);">deferred tax asset</span>.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;"><strong>What does deferred tax mean in practice?</strong><br>It is about <em>when</em> you get the deduction, not necessarily whether you get it. Tax declining balance often gives larger deductions early, while accounting depreciation follows the accounting plan. This creates temporary differences and deferred tax/deferred tax assets. Total deductions are normally the same over time, but the timing may differ.</p><p style="margin:0;opacity:.7;font-size:12px;">Use the <strong>Compare</strong> mode to see concrete figures for the difference between methods.</p></div>',
